Hi lsalsich!

Ansible-cmdb should already do what you want it to do in basically the exact way you're trying to do it. The facts from a hosts's `/etc/ansible/facts.d/` should appear under a heading "Host local facts". I do exactly the same thing. Can you verify that when you execute:

    ansible -m setup --tree out/ all

The output for one of the hosts in `out/` actually contains a structure similar to this (some stuff stripped for brevity sake):

    {
       "changed" : false,
       "failed" : false,
       "ansible_facts" : {
          "ansible_local" : {
             "firewall_status" : {
                "policy_drop_v6" : false,
                "ufw_enabled" : true,
                "firewall_detection" : true,
                "policy_drop_v4" : false,
                "ferm_enabled" : false
             },
             "services" : {
                "services" : [
                   {
                      "users" : [],
                      "protocol" : "tcp",
                      "port" : "*:43302"
                   },
                ]
             }
          }
       }
    }

The fact that you have them in `"ansible_local": { "custom_facts": { "services":` shouldn't matter at all. The method of showing that information is to just recursively dump everything under "ansible_local" to the output file. So it should already include your info.

