@hmaarrfk It can't really be applied to that since this is not a trivial function – as in not one that we know what it does (from the docstring).

However, going back to its usage in helper functions at the minimum, this opens up a whole realm of possibilities for cleaner code in general.

At my university, we have a saying: "one function per task, one task per function." These guidelines make it incredibly easy to read and modify functional code – everything is compartmentalized and also open to testing. This also makes it easier to create abstractions without increasing code clutter. However, in Python this is less-than-optimal because you are forced to choose between readability and proper documentation.

